<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09154f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09154f">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09154f"> 154(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Civis = fence</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Thus starting with such a &ldquo;stockade&rdquo; = &ldquo;city&rdquo; analogy, you soon see many other verbal babies born of this etymological union. It is a matter, too, not of twins, but triplets, for &ldquo;civility,&rdquo; &ldquo;politeness&rdquo; and &ldquo;urbanity&rdquo; are all three easily from <i>civis, polis, urbs</i> = a city. The picture is that of the coarse country bumpkin versus the five-fold <i>polished, polite, civil, urbane</i> city dweller, with (same root!) the policeman at hand, all five forms being from civis, <mark>a city = a fence</mark>. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 149</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
